Here's how to implement all three pieces:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form here -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with cancel command and dirty tracking

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    public IRelayCommand CancelCommand { get; }

    public EditProductViewModel()
    {
        CancelCommand = new AsyncRelayCommand(OnCancelAsync);
    }

    private async Task OnCancelAsync()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                return; // user chose to stay
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Guard the hardware/gesture back button in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

The custom `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the **shell back button**, but the Android hardware back button and swipe-back gesture fire through `OnNavigating`. Guard those too:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back navigation (Pop)
    if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
        return;

    // Check if the current page's BindingContext has unsaved changes
    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage?.BindingContext
            is EditProductViewModel vm && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

### How it works

| Trigger | Handled by |
|---|---|
| Shell back arrow (now says "Cancel") | `BackButtonBehavior.Command` → `CancelCommand` |
| Android hardware back / swipe gesture | `OnNavigating` guard with `GetDeferral()` |

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user chooses "Stay".
- Set `HasUnsavedChanges = true` whenever a form field changes (e.g., via property setters or `TextChanged` events).
